The paper discusses the interplay between machine learning and differential privacy, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also focuses on privacy-preserving algorithms and data release mechanisms, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). Additionally, the paper mentions theoretical results related to loss functions and what can be learned differentially privately, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the use of private datasets, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.DB (Databases). Finally, the paper presents open questions related to the scalability of differentially private machine learning algorithms, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
